                <h2>Knowing Delta Airlines Pet Policies</h2>

                <p>Before you gear up and plan your trip with your pet you must be accustomed to the pet policies that there are in place. Knowing these policies will help you to have a seamless and smooth flight with your pets. The policies can be spoken about as the following –</p>
                <p>You can carry small dogs, cats, or household birds as your carry-on pets. Given you pay a one-way fee that you will have to deposit during the check-in. Your pet must fit in a soft side ventilated kennel which goes right underneath the seat in front of you. To ensure a safe and healthy flight your pet must fit the following categories –</p>
                <p><b>1.</b> Your pet should be of least 8 weeks old for domestic travel.</p>
                <p><b>2.</b> If you are traveling to the US from another country your cat must of sixteen weeks of age, and a dog must at least be six months old.</p>
                <p><b>3.</b> If you are travelling to the European Union your pet must at least be 15 weeks old.</p>
                <p><b>4.</b> One pet is permitted for per kennel with exceptions as-</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>You can bring along 1 female cat or dog with their unweaned litter which should be between 8 weeks to 6 months old. There is so much limiting on how many animals as long as they fit the kennel.</li>
                    <li>You can also take two pets of the exact same breed and the exact same  size, which are allowed to travel given they are 8 weeks to six months of age and are small enough to fit in a single kennel.</li>
                    <li>Pets in the kennel as taken as your one carry-on item, in addition to this, you are allowed to bring only one personal item on board.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Note- This airline has a first come first serve policy set in place for pets, hence there can only be a certain amount of pets in one flight.</p>

